b'' b'on sun may damon wrote:' b'' b' a christian friend of mine once reasoned that if we were never' b' created, we could not exists. therefore we were created, and' b' therefore there exists a creator.' b'' b'i hesitate to comment on the validity of this, because i do not know' b'what your friend meant by it. if he meant that whatever exists must' b'have been created, then he is open to the obvious retort that god' b'exists, and so god must have been created.' b'' b'perhaps your friend meant that we exist now but that there was a' b'time when we did not exist, and therefore something other than' b'ourselves must have brought us into existence. this seems plausible,' b'but an atheist might reply, "so my parents engendered me. so what?"' b'here your friend would have to explain why an infinite regress of' b'causes is not a satisfactory explanation. he would have some support' b'from philosophers who are not ordinarily considered religious (ayn' b'rand, and some others who are in the tradition of aristotle). having' b'argued for a first cause, he would have to bridge the gap between' b'said entity and the god of abraham. if he merely asserts that the' b'things we observe are ultimately dependent on things radically' b'unlike them, few physicists would disagree.' b'' b'yours,' b'james kiefer' 